* Why is recovery important  
  ![][image17]  
  “Not the reason to choose David” but Why Recovery is Important  
  All other words in the paragraph shown above is  (**content to be provided by client**)  
  *“RCL”* was born out of the founder Slade Skaggs’ personal experience in and out of sober living throughout his active struggle against personal addiction for over 25 years. Geared toward helping men & women coming out of short-term and long-term treatment or those who have integrated a regular and routine practice for their walk-in recovery,Recovery Centered Living a safe, sober, clean, and spiritual environment to transition to when they discharge or when they find the need for community.Our recovery residences provide and create an environment where individuals are encouraged to take actions that say and show that those living a life in recovery not only love themselves but others as well as their community at large. All while learning to be productive members of society and improving their overall quality of life.Our unique recovery living model and recovery houses offer those who need help a peer-led environment where all included have lived through this life experience and inspire hope, strength, and courage in one another.Quite simply, those living in RCL houses take their rightful place in this sacred circle of healing and know that we are warriors laying down our shields and surrender to the beat of our heart, so we may become peaceful, forgiving, and truly productive members of society.  
    
  Here is some more content for info as well:

  Recovery Centered Living has been in business for over 3½ years and we are a Recovery Residence with a family-oriented culture & Community. We have a model that was built from other organizations’ direction and guidance that they have evidence-based practices and guidelines built from more than 20 years of experience in the Recovery Residence field.

I myself am a person in Long-term recovery and have been set on a mission with a vision to be of service, support, and hold space for people in recovery. By creating environments where people can learn to be productive & empowered healthy members of society.

RCL has had the opportunity over the last few years to open 3 Recover Residences RCL1 & 2 men’s homes and most recently is RCL3 women’s home. We are excited to expand our homes to provide the culture we hold dear and offer a place for individuals wanting a new way of life with community

Our model is one of high accountability for the members living at RCL, we have days that chores must be done to maintain the integrity of the inside of the house as well as keeping the yard and outside well-groomed. There are guidelines and contracts for membership in place that allow Me, the onsite Manager & Assistant manager to discharge them and remove their digital key code at any moment for any reason deemed necessary. We maintain a safe, sober, and spiritual environment and will not allow anything outside of that. I am including our list of guidelines that protect the house as a whole and individuals living there.
